    <main>
        <section id="home">
            <h2>Welcome to PC Components Guide</h2>
            <p>Learn about the different parts that make up a PC and how they work together to create a functional computer.</p>
        </section>
        <section id="cpu">
            <h2>CPU (Central Processing Unit)</h2>
            <p>The CPU is the brain of the computer. It performs calculations and executes instructions to run programs.</p>
        </section>
        <section id="gpu">
            <h2>GPU (Graphics Processing Unit)</h2>
            <p>The GPU is responsible for rendering images, videos, and animations. It's essential for gaming and video editing.</p>
        </section>
        <section id="ram">
            <h2>RAM (Random Access Memory)</h2>
            <p>RAM is the short-term memory of the computer. It stores data that the CPU needs quick access to while running programs.</p>
        </section>
        <section id="motherboard">
            <h2>Motherboard</h2>
            <p>The motherboard is the main circuit board that connects all the components of the PC. It allows them to communicate with each other.</p>
        </section>
        <section id="storage">
            <h2>Storage (HDD and SSD)</h2>
            <p>Storage devices like HDDs and SSDs are used to store data permanently. SSDs are faster and more reliable than HDDs.</p>
        </section>
        <section id="psu">
            <h2>PSU (Power Supply Unit)</h2>
            <p>The PSU converts electrical power from an outlet into a usable form for the other components of the PC.</p>
        </section>
        <section id="cooling">
            <h2>Cooling System</h2>
            <p>Cooling systems keep the temperature of the components down to prevent overheating and maintain performance.</p>
        </section>
        <section id="case">
            <h2>Case</h2>
            <p>The case houses all the components of the PC. It also provides ventilation and protection for the internal parts.</p>
        </section>
        <section id="how-it-works">
            <h2>How It Works</h2>
            <p>When you power on your PC, the PSU supplies power to the motherboard and other components. The CPU processes instructions from the operating system and software, while the RAM provides quick access to data. The GPU renders visuals, and storage devices retain your data. Cooling systems ensure everything runs smoothly without overheating.</p>
        </section>
    </main>
